Harrisburg University of Science and Technology
Claim Summary.
This replication tests the claim that realistic threat tested at time 1 was positively associated with negative affect experiences over the course of a subsequent week (time 2). This claim was assessed with a structural equation model with all criterion outcomes tested simultaneously in one model. 
Replication Criteria.
Criteria for a successful replication attempt for the SCORE project is a statistically significant effect (alpha = .05, two tailed) in the same pattern as the original study on the focal hypothesis test (H*). For this study, a successful replication is a positive coefficient on the term for realistic threat at time 1 in the SEM predicting negative affect one week later.
Replication Result.
This replication included 346 participants with 262 participants completing both time points of the study and 84 who were excluded for only completing one time point of the study. With our manipulation checks, we excluded 7 participants who had taken both weeks of the study (n = 255) and 9 participants (n = 75) who had only taken one week of the study. After creating composite scores and merging the two time points, we were left with 246 participants in the SEM analysis (see lavaan output under Used versus Total). This met our target analytic sample size (n = 243). The SEM parameter estimates indicate that the path coefficient (b) for realistic threat at time 1 was b = 1.56, SE = 1.00, 95%CI [-0.41, 3.52], Z = 1.55, p = .1202667. While this effect is in the same direction as the original result, we would not consider this result to have replicated due to our criteria of p < .05. The parameter estimates are provided below. 


How to interpret the table:
All .x values are time 1, all .y values are time 2.
The single ~ symbol represents regression, therefore is read as Y is predicted by X. The first example BAI_total.y ~ Realistic.x can be understood as BAI total at time 2 predicted by Realistic threat at time 1. 
The double ~~ symbol represents either covariance or variance. If the left hand side and right hand side are different (BAI_total.y ~~ Avoidance.y), this implies covariance between the two variables because b is unstandardized. If the left and right hand sides are the same (BAI_total.y ~~ BAI_total.y), this value represents the variance found in that variable in the model. 

Deviations from preregistration.
The preregistration code was updated with the following:
Deidentification to ensure Prolific IDs were not shared.
Code to help with the reproducibility (i.e., information on operating systems and versions).
Excluded all test data because this is part of the raw data download.
Excluded duplicates from participants taking the survey twice or opening and closing the survey several times within the same week.
Matching participants when IDs were not recorded.
Originally, we planned to hand score the attention check dog item. We did do that during the running of the study to know who to pay/keep track of participants.  However, we updated the code in the analysis document to reflect our scoring using regular expressions to be clear and reproducible on what we thought reflected a correct answer. 
The section on allowable missing data was not included in the original code, as it was created with complete data. The section from our preregistration was pasted into the analysis section and code for those rules was added/updated to reflect our plan. 
No deviations were made for the study delivery. 
Description of materials provided.
Methods and Materials: https://osf.io/y2qv5/ 
The Kachanoff_Survey excel file includes the formr coding to create the survey. This format includes all the items and answer choices, which allows recreation of the survey by uploading into formr. 
The Materials document file represents the items shown to participants as a word document that was submitted to the IRB. 
The dog_image would be required to recreate the survey, and represents the manipulation check shown to participants. 
Data: https://osf.io/3cavs/ 
Kachanoff_DataDictionary excel file includes a data dictionary for the dataset with all variables explained and choice numbers identified. 
Kachanoff_Survey_deidentify csv file includes the deidentified data. This data was simply processed to exclude Prolific ID numbers, which are not anonymous. You can see the code that created the new column and dropped the Prolific ID column in our Analysis folder. 
Kachanoff_Survey_example csv file is an example dataset that was used to provide preregistration code. 
Analysis: https://osf.io/xshv6/ 
The Analysis rmd (R markdown) and html file are the original preregistered scripts that provided an outline for the analysis.
The Analysis_updated rmd and html file are the updated analysis scripts with the fixed analysis and new code described above. This file can be used to recreate our analyses. Note, you will need to download the full OSF structure to recreate these analyses, as we incorporated the file structure into our script (i.e., it is expected that the markdown file is in a folder Analysis and the data is in a folder Data). Note that the versions of R and packages are provided at the top of the html report for full reproducibility. 
All materials will be made public.
Citation.
Kachanoff, F., Bigman, Y.E., Kapsaskis, K., Gray, K. (2020). Measuring two distinct psychological threats of COVID-19 and their unique impacts on wellbeing and adherence to public health behaviors. https://doi.org/10.31234/osf.io/5zr3w
